dropbead tutorial

NIkolaos Karaiskos

21 Apr 2016

There are two main classes to store samples, SingleSpeciesSample and MixedSpeciesSample, the latter containing the former.

Mixed species experiments

These experiments are important to estimate the number of doublets in the samples. The package assumes that a digital gene expression matrix (DGE) has already been generated. The human/mouse genes are distinguished by the prefix hg_ and mm_ respectively. Assuming that the DGE has been loaded in dge.matrix,

# The object containing the sample
mms <- new("MixedSpeciesSample", species1="human", species2="mouse",
           dge=dge.matrix)

The number of cells and genes are stored and automatically updated while using the functions of dropbead

length(mms@cells)
## [1] 1199
length(mms@genes)
## [1] 42367

Calling classifyCellsAndDoublets separates the species and returns a data.frame with number of transcripts per cell per species.

head(classifyCellsAndDoublets(mms, threshold = 0.9, min.trans = 300))
##           cell human mouse species
## 1 TTGAGACGGATA 33220   500   human
## 2 TTGCAGCCACCT 32693   477   human
## 3 GCTTCAGACAGA 31593   448   human
## 4 CTCTTCATCGAG 28261   338   human
## 5 TAACACACCGTG   529 30639   mouse
## 6 AGCTGCCGTTTG   565 29027   mouse

The output can be send for plotting

plotCellTypes(classifyCellsAndDoublets(mms))

Number of genes per cell is computed via

head(computeGenesPerCell(mms, min.reads = 1))
##          cells counts species
## 1 TTGAGACGGATA   7825   human
## 2 TTGCAGCCACCT   7821   human
## 3 GCTTCAGACAGA   7773   human
## 4 CTCTTCATCGAG   7479   human
## 5 GCTTACTATCCG   7037   human
## 6 AACTGGTTCGTC   6883   human

and similarly for transcripts. The user can send the output for plotting

plotViolin(computeTranscriptsPerCell(mms), attribute = "transcripts")

The functions are polymorphic and can be used for SingleSpeciesSample objects. Splitting the samples is always performed by internal functions. If the user wants to restrict to one species, this is done by

h <- splitMixedSpeciesSampleToSingleSpecies(mms, threshold = 0.9)[[1]]
class(h)
## [1] "SingleSpeciesSample"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "dropseq"

which returns a list of two SingleSpeciesSample objects.

Single species

There are a couple of functions to remove low quality cells and genes, such as

h.f1 <- keepBestCells(h, num.cells = 100)
h.f2 <- keepBestCells(h, min.num.trans = 1000)
h.f3 <- removeLowQualityCells(h, min.genes = 2000)
h.f4 <- removeLowQualityGenes(h, min.cells = 3)

with obvious usage. Other very useful functions are to compare samples against each other, or against bulk data when available. For instance,

compareGeneExpressionLevels(h.f1, h.f2)

compareSingleCellsAgainstBulk(h.f1, log(h.f2@dge[, 1, drop=F]+1))
